[WARNING]

This article discusses ReactiveCocoa (RAC) practices in the Objective-C era. Although the technology stack has shifted to Swift/Combine, the memory management and design pattern thinking involved still have reference value.

After much anticipation, I finally adopted RAC code in my new project. I used RAC extensively in a project a long time ago without much consideration for its side effects. Now, I'm finally using it in a large project, but when it comes to performance optimization, I find that the performance gains from RAC are worth reconsidering.

I won't go into the internal implementation and code architecture of RAC, or the various points discussed online. Here, I'll mainly talk about the problems I encountered.

These include:

1. Circular references.

2. Multi-level KayPaths in KVO.

3. Code overhead.

## Circular References

Let's look at the problem of circular references through two cases.

### CASE ONE

Let's first look at...`RACObserve`The implementation details and why circular references are prone to occur:

```mermaid
graph TD
    Block["Block (implicitly retains self)"] -->|Captures| Self["self"]
    Self -->|Holds| Signal["RACSignal"]
    Signal -->|Subscribes| Block

    style Block fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px
    style Self fill:#bbf,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px
    style Signal fill:#bfb,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px

    linkStyle 0,1,2 stroke:red,stroke-width:2px;
```Let's first look at the implementation of RACObserve.

```objc
#define _RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) \
({ \
    __weak id target_ = (TARGET); \
    [target_ rac_valuesForKeyPath:@keypath(TARGET, KEYPATH) observer:self]; \
})

#if __clang__ && (__clang_major__ >= 8)
#define RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) _RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH)
#else
#define RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) \
({ \
    _Pragma("clang diagnostic push") \
    _Pragma("clang diagnostic ignored \"-Wreceiver-is-weak\"") \
    _RACObserve(TARGET, KEYPATH) \
    _Pragma("clang diagnostic pop") \
})
#endif
```This code clearly shows that `self` after `Target` is inserted.

Now let's look at the following code snippet, from the official source code.

```objc
// Observes self, and doesn't stop until self is deallocated.
RACSignal *selfSignal = RACObserve(self, arrayController.items);

// Observes the array controller, and stops when self _or_ the array
// controller is deallocated.
RACSignal *arrayControllerSignal = RACObserve(self.arrayController, items);

// Observes obj.arrayController, and stops when self _or_ the array
// controller is deallocated.
RACSignal *signal2 = RACObserve(obj.arrayController, items);

@weakify(self);
RACSignal *signal3 = [anotherSignal flattenMap:^(NSArrayController *arrayController) {
// Avoids a retain cycle because of RACObserve implicitly referencing
// self.
@strongify(self);
return RACObserve(arrayController, items);
}];
```Official Explanation

> Creates a signal which observes`KEYPATH` on `TARGET` for changes.
In either case, the observation continues until `TARGET` _or self_ is
deallocated. If any intermediate object is deallocated instead, it will be
assumed to have been set to nil.
Make sure to `@strongify(self)` when using this macro within a block! The
macro will _always_ reference `self`, which can silently introduce a retain
cycle within a block. As a result, you should make sure that `self` is a weak
reference (e.g., created by `@weakify` and `@strongify`) before the
expression that uses `RACObserve`In short, a `RACObserve` was used in a `RAC` block, but `@strongify` wasn't used again (i.e., it wasn't weakly transformed), causing the `Cycle` to be retained.

### CASE TWO

`RACSubject` is a bridge between non-RAC and RAC code. Refer to the tutorials on GitHub for usage examples.

Here's a scenario I encountered, with the code below:

```objc
@implementation UIImageView (Demo)

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url{
   return [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:nil];
}

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder{
    if (url.absoluteString.length == 0) {
        [self cancelCurrentImageLoad];
        self.image = placeholder;
        return [RACSignal empty];
    }
    RACSubject *subject = [RACSubject subject];
    if (self.frame.size.width == 0 && self.frame.size.height == 0) {
        dispatch_async(dispatch_get_main_queue(), ^{
            [self rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:subject];
        });
    }else{
        [self rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:subject];
    }
    return [subject deliverOnMainThread];
}

-(void)rbs_executeWithUrl:(NSURL*)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder subject:(RACSubject*)subject{
    [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:placeholder completed:^(UIImage * _Nullable image, NSError * _Nullable error, RBSImageCacheType cacheType, NSURL * _Nullable imageURL) {
        if(image && !error){
            [subject sendNext:image];
        }else{
            [subject sendError:error];
        }
    }];
}
@end
```

Did you spot the problem? If not, and you're unfamiliar with the implementation of RACSubject or online resources, you wouldn't understand why this part is identified as "leaky" in the Leak Profile.

The gist is that RACSubject's release is only triggered by the protocol calls to SendNext, sendError, and sendComp. From a purely code-driven perspective, this seems correct.

However, the current scenario involves asynchronous operations and the possibility of further calls. The thrown object is held by the outer layer, causing the problem of it not being actively released.

There are two possible solutions: one is for the caller to be responsible, and the other is automatic release, where the ImageView category is automatically released when it's deallocated.

Due to the project's specifics, I'll discuss the second approach here.

How is automatic release when the ImageView category is deallocated implemented?

RAC internally performs a deallocation swizz, which is triggered by a dedicated dispatch object.

The revised approach (this change also modified the lifecycle and usage of weak objects because the GCD switching call will be executed in the next main loop, which would cause problems if the current object is released)

```objc
@implementation UIImageView (Demo)

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url{
   return [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:nil];
}

- (RACSignal*)rbs_setImageWithURL:(NSURL *)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder{
    if (url.absoluteString.length == 0) {
        [self cancelCurrentImageLoad];
        self.image = placeholder;
        return [RACSignal empty];
    }
    RACSubject *subject = [RACSubject subject];
    if (self.frame.size.width == 0 && self.frame.size.height == 0) {
        _weak typeof(self) weakSelf = self;
        __weak typeof(subject) weakSubject = subject;
        dispatch_async(dispatch_get_main_queue(), ^{
            [weakSelf rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:weakSubject];
        });
    }else{
        [self rbs_executeWithUrl:url placeholderImage:placeholder subject:subject];
    }
    return [[subject deliverOnMainThread] takeUntil:self.rac_willDeallocSignal];
}

-(void)rbs_executeWithUrl:(NSURL*)url placeholderImage:(UIImage *)placeholder subject:(RACSubject*)subject{
    __weak typeof(subject) weakSubject = subject;
    [self rbs_setImageWithURL:url placeholderImage:placeholder completed:^(UIImage * _Nullable image, NSError * _Nullable error, RBSImageCacheType cacheType, NSURL * _Nullable imageURL) {
        if(image && !error){
            [weakSubject sendNext:image];
        }else{
            [weakSubject sendError:error];
        }
    }];
}
@end
```The `takeUntil:self.rac_willDeallocSignal` line is what resolves the leakage issue.

> `[[subject deliverOnMainThread] takeUntil:self.rac_willDeallocSignal]`

In summary: When using `RACSubject`, it's crucial to understand its underlying mechanisms. `RACSubject` generates a hot signal; its internal `subscribeNext` calls trigger `map`, which then calls `bind`. `bind` internally blocks its own operations.

In its design, RAC requires manual intervention for unpacking certain operations, leading to various difficulties for beginners. While some might say it will improve after this initial period, this requires an experienced RAC programmer within the team.

## Multi-level KeyPaths in KVO

Let's get straight to the point. As everyone knows, Cocoa's KVO only supports single-level KeyPaths, which are the current level of the Observer. Cross-level KeyPaths become more complex. One scenario introduced by RAC is solving multi-level KeyPaths. The `RACKVOWrapper` category is an example of this multi-level implementation.

The idea is to use the current level's Observer to access the next level of the KeyPath, recursively going down the hierarchy until the last level of the KeyPaths. The implementation is 201 lines of code, but the related business logic involves eight header files.

Simply put, it first needs to parse the original KeyPaths path, using the runtime of the first-level KeyPath to access the next level of the KeyPath. This process is continuous. Then, the parsed `rac_propertyAttributes` of each level is stored in a collection data structure.

### Building Your Own Wheel

Some might suggest using the second-to-last level of the KeyPaths as the Observer and the last level as the final KeyPath in Cocoa, which would solve the problem.

However, this isn't the case. For example, if every level of the KeyPaths has already been instantiated, there's no problem. But if the Observer is defined in `init`, and a certain level of another KeyPaths hasn't been instantiated, the custom KVO will fail.

Another example: if all levels of the KeyPaths have been instantiated, the above solution succeeds. But if you suddenly set a certain level of a previously constructed KeyPaths to nil and then reinitialize it, KVO will fail again.

The above solution simply won't work.

## Code Consumption

The RAC codebase is indeed quite large. The packaged parts include C and Objective-C, and then there are locks for various scenarios.

The code for RAC's various business scenario layers accounts for 533k of code files, spanning 190 files. Even for just one scenario, this accounts for a significant portion of the operations.

Let's talk about locks first. As a commonly used business logic in projects, it's used on the main thread, and RAC provides a wide range of lock scenarios, basically covering all common locks.

The `RACKVOWrapper` class mentioned above involves some RAC signal-related code, and each layer of KeyPaths parsing adds another layer of overhead.

There are many business scenarios involved, so I won't list them all here. Considering only one aspect is impractical. We must address each specific business need; there's no need to use a sledgehammer to crack a nut.

## Future Directions

Our business logic includes RAC, which hinders our critical path performance. We've tried replacing `RACObserve` with KVO and blocks, but this blocks the implementation of multi-level KVO. We're considering writing our own multi-level KeyPaths solution, keeping it lightweight to address the current business needs for refactoring. In the future, we'll prioritize event-driven implementations over excessive KVO. KVO is like an iceberg in the ocean—too much is unsafe and unstable. The concept of RAC is good, but it can be implemented in other ways. Without business needs, there's no technology.
